Marques I love you but I have to say this. First off thank you for your genuine consumer advice. Also giving a lot of us access to things we'll never know. I just can't bear hearing "2 eks, 3 eks, 10 eks zoom" any more. For a tech channel with such reach it's horrendous. The amount of photography you do you should know better. You don't say "two eks fives equals ten" do you? It's math. It's multiplication. You're magnifying an image an ampunt of times. 3x zoom means three times multiplication. That's why we use the letter x. Please don't perpetuate knowledge. There will come a point where people say "10 eks" zoom and they've no idea where the x comes from. It's important we know why things are what they are, especially in the science of technology. 3x is 3 times magnification of the standard lens. Or 3x zoom. Or 3 times. Please. Anyway, thanks for your time. (Not your eks)

ğŸ˜­I'm trying everywhere, just hoping you see this  Hey Marques,   Iâ€™m writing this feeling a mix of hope and embarrassment, but Iâ€™ve been a fan for so long that I feel like I have to try.   I found your channel in 2017, and it honestly changed how I see tech. I've watched every single episode since. I don't just enjoy your videos, I study them. The video production is something like magic to me. You made me love tech, and your reviews are the final word for me for any tech purchase I even think about. The reason I'm writing, and why this is so awkward, is that my reality is a world away from that dream. I'm a 4th-year pharmacy student at Levy Mwanawasa Medical University in Zambia, and to be honest, this year has been one of the toughest of my life. My phone was stolen in May, and then, cruelly, again in June. My laptop, which was my lifeline for research and assignments, has completely died. It's gone.  Trying to keep up with the research and assignments for my degree without a computer or a reliable phone has been a nightmare. Itâ€™s isolating and incredibly stressful. My parents, who have already sacrificed so much, simply can't afford to replace them. I feel like I'm failing, and the stress is overwhelming.   I know you probably get messages like this all the time (and I hope i don't find myself in your spam folder ğŸ˜­), and I feel a little embarrassed even asking, but I thought, if there's even a tiny chance you see this and help, it would literally change my life. If not, that's totally okay...really. Just knowing you might read this and know that your work inspires someone like me, fighting through a tough situation thousands of miles away, would mean a lot, It makes me feel a little less alone in this.   Thanks for all the inspiration over the years. It means more than you know.   Sincerely,  Tionge Nyirenda from Zambia.

Diagonal screen size is a REALLY flawed metric for measuring phone size and portability, because it ignores the rise of bezelless screens  Example: base S25 is very one-handable at only 2.78" wide. This isn't much more than the iPhone 6, at 2.64" wide. yet when we compare their diagonals  (6.2" Vs 4.7") it seems like an insane difference. This is due to the iPhone 6's 16:9 screen  Essentially the S25 and iPhone 6 have a very similar physical size footprint. So it doesn't make sense to deride one for being 6+in and praise the other for being 4.7in. That's only their display size  For further comparison, take the 5.1" Galaxy S5, which is actually wider than the S25 at 2.85". (Admittedly, it is shorter, but I'd argue width matters for one-handed use. Height doesn't really affect anything). Even though the phone has a smaller diagonal screen size by a whole 1.18", it still works out to be harder to use one-handed  If your issue is with the lack of even smaller (i.e. iPhone 5-sized) phones anymore, then fair enough. But even then, there's still fairly modern options (iPhone 13 mini, iPhone SE 3, Asus ZenFone 9)

I disagree with the sentiment that Pixels are software-focus only phone. I think Pixel still carries the Nexus spirit into today as a "reference" phone. It's supposed to set the tone for the rest of the industry. Pixel a for low budget, Pixel for mid-tier, Pixel Pro for the premium device, and fold for the foldable device which is a device category of its own like a tablet is. It's supposed to signal to the consumer this is what you can expect from an Android phone at this price point. Other manufacturers could "compete" by doing something different like throwing bigger hardware at it, or providing niche hardware options. I think the Pixel-exclusive software is just Google putting in their own advertisements to upsell their own services to get you to subscribe, or have exclusive right to mine your data like Photo AI edit. There aren't that many truly Pixel-exclusive that ends up being truly free to Pixel owners.

They're still low volume products. Regular phone screens, tvs, and monitors all share the same panels so they benefit from economies of scale. Curved displays and folding phones use the same panels but people generally don't want curved displays. So the market is much smaller meaning costs won't come down as quickly if at all.   The reason for this is that the cost to produce a single panel is very high but almost all of that cost is in the manufacturing process itself. Once the mfg line is built, the panels themselves are relatively cheap. If the panel maker can sell 1000s of panels, then the costs come way down as they are able to spread the start up cost over many more units sold
